[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":448},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects\u002F":424,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects\u002F":433},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190518\u002F2008223156\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":407,"date":408,"description":409,"extension":410,"lang":411,"meta":412,"navigation":178,"path":413,"readingMinutes":414,"seo":415,"standalone":416,"stem":417,"tags":418,"tldr":421,"updated":408,"url":422,"__hash__":423},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects.md","[JS Weird World] No.26 Functions Are Just Objects","1000142545",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":402},"minimark",[11,16,25,31,38,41,47,50,63,69,72,80,86,89,141,144,195,202,208,214,277,283,290,348,353,359,365,368,374,378,387,391,398],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"functions-are-just-objects","Functions Are Just Objects",[17,18,19,20,24],"p",{},"\"Functions are objects\" — that title probably leaves a lot of you a little confused, and honestly that's fair. So let's go back to one of the most basic, most fundamental concepts in JavaScript. Understanding it is what lets you go beyond just using JavaScript and start treating it as a tool other languages can't quite match. The concept is called ",[21,22,23],"strong",{},"first-class functions",".",[17,26,27,28,24],{},"In the JavaScript world, this boils down to one idea: ",[21,29,30],{},"functions are objects",[17,32,33],{},[34,35],"img",{"alt":36,"src":37},"Functions are objects","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FfXt3RQZ.png",[17,39,40],{},"JavaScript isn't the only language with first-class functions, by the way. The course explains it a bit vaguely, so I pulled a clearer description from pjchender about what first-class functions actually are ↓",[17,42,43],{},[34,44],{"alt":45,"src":46},"pjchender on first-class functions","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FVDopF09.png",[17,48,49],{},"So what's a function object? The course had a nice diagram for this. It's a special kind of object — it has all the traits of a regular object plus some extra properties.",[51,52,53,57,60],"ul",{},[54,55,56],"li",{},"A function can be tied to name\u002Fvalue pairs",[54,58,59],{},"It can hold other objects",[54,61,62],{},"It can hold other functions",[17,64,65],{},[34,66],{"alt":67,"src":68},"Function object","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FXwWJkAq.png",[17,70,71],{},"There are also a couple of special properties in JavaScript:",[51,73,74,77],{},[54,75,76],{},"A function doesn't have to have a name",[54,78,79],{},"And one that's a bit more unusual — a code property, also called the code block",[17,81,82],{},[34,83],{"alt":84,"src":85},"Special properties","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FLQ4NjUV.png",[17,87,88],{},"Maybe it's clearer if we just look at some code.",[90,91,96],"pre",{"className":92,"code":93,"language":94,"meta":95,"style":95},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n}\n\n","js","",[97,98,99,116,135],"code",{"__ignoreMap":95},[100,101,104,108,112],"span",{"class":102,"line":103},"line",1,[100,105,107],{"class":106},"sWyjQ","function",[100,109,111],{"class":110},"sj_SG"," greet",[100,113,115],{"class":114},"sMAXC","() {\n",[100,117,119,122,125,128,132],{"class":102,"line":118},2,[100,120,121],{"class":114}," console.",[100,123,124],{"class":110},"log",[100,126,127],{"class":114},"(",[100,129,131],{"class":130},"sTRMh","'hi'",[100,133,134],{"class":114},");\n",[100,136,138],{"class":102,"line":137},3,[100,139,140],{"class":114},"}\n",[17,142,143],{},"Here's the idea to keep in mind: functions are objects, so we can use the dot operator to add stuff to them, just like an object.",[90,145,147],{"className":92,"code":146,"language":94,"meta":95,"style":95},"function greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n}\n\ngreet.language = 'english';\n",[97,148,149,157,169,173,180],{"__ignoreMap":95},[100,150,151,153,155],{"class":102,"line":103},[100,152,107],{"class":106},[100,154,111],{"class":110},[100,156,115],{"class":114},[100,158,159,161,163,165,167],{"class":102,"line":118},[100,160,121],{"class":114},[100,162,124],{"class":110},[100,164,127],{"class":114},[100,166,131],{"class":130},[100,168,134],{"class":114},[100,170,171],{"class":102,"line":137},[100,172,140],{"class":114},[100,174,176],{"class":102,"line":175},4,[100,177,179],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":178},true,"\n",[100,181,183,186,189,192],{"class":102,"line":182},5,[100,184,185],{"class":114},"greet.language ",[100,187,188],{"class":106},"=",[100,190,191],{"class":130}," 'english'",[100,193,194],{"class":114},";\n",[17,196,197,198,201],{},"In most other languages you can't do this — you'd get an error, guaranteed. But JavaScript lets you. And if we ",[97,199,200],{},"console.log"," it here, something interesting happens.",[17,203,204],{},[34,205],{"alt":206,"src":207},"hi","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FS6fcrDm.png",[17,209,210,211,213],{},"We only got ",[97,212,206],{},". So where's english? Let's try to find it like this:",[90,215,217],{"className":92,"code":216,"language":94,"meta":95,"style":95},"function greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n}\n\ngreet.language = 'english';\ngreet()\nconsole.log(greet.language);\n",[97,218,219,227,239,243,247,257,266],{"__ignoreMap":95},[100,220,221,223,225],{"class":102,"line":103},[100,222,107],{"class":106},[100,224,111],{"class":110},[100,226,115],{"class":114},[100,228,229,231,233,235,237],{"class":102,"line":118},[100,230,121],{"class":114},[100,232,124],{"class":110},[100,234,127],{"class":114},[100,236,131],{"class":130},[100,238,134],{"class":114},[100,240,241],{"class":102,"line":137},[100,242,140],{"class":114},[100,244,245],{"class":102,"line":175},[100,246,179],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":178},[100,248,249,251,253,255],{"class":102,"line":182},[100,250,185],{"class":114},[100,252,188],{"class":106},[100,254,191],{"class":130},[100,256,194],{"class":114},[100,258,260,263],{"class":102,"line":259},6,[100,261,262],{"class":110},"greet",[100,264,265],{"class":114},"()\n",[100,267,269,272,274],{"class":102,"line":268},7,[100,270,271],{"class":114},"console.",[100,273,124],{"class":110},[100,275,276],{"class":114},"(greet.language);\n",[17,278,279],{},[34,280],{"alt":281,"src":282},"greet.language","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FRG8Qm5z.png",[17,284,285,286,289],{},"Oh — there it is, we can find ",[97,287,288],{},"language",". So what do we get if we write it like this?",[90,291,293],{"className":92,"code":292,"language":94,"meta":95,"style":95},"function greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n}\n\ngreet.language = 'english';\ngreet()\nconsole.log(greet);\n",[97,294,295,303,315,319,323,333,339],{"__ignoreMap":95},[100,296,297,299,301],{"class":102,"line":103},[100,298,107],{"class":106},[100,300,111],{"class":110},[100,302,115],{"class":114},[100,304,305,307,309,311,313],{"class":102,"line":118},[100,306,121],{"class":114},[100,308,124],{"class":110},[100,310,127],{"class":114},[100,312,131],{"class":130},[100,314,134],{"class":114},[100,316,317],{"class":102,"line":137},[100,318,140],{"class":114},[100,320,321],{"class":102,"line":175},[100,322,179],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":178},[100,324,325,327,329,331],{"class":102,"line":182},[100,326,185],{"class":114},[100,328,188],{"class":106},[100,330,191],{"class":130},[100,332,194],{"class":114},[100,334,335,337],{"class":102,"line":259},[100,336,262],{"class":110},[100,338,265],{"class":114},[100,340,341,343,345],{"class":102,"line":268},[100,342,271],{"class":114},[100,344,124],{"cl